pr_review_comment_body:
@Tschanzt can you fix the indenting?
Please use the same indenting settings as in the rest of the document (local consistency) 😉 
thanks!

Of course, the other option if you prefer it is probably more Pythonic:

```python
try:
    server_certificate = socket.getpeercert(True)
except AttributeError:
    warnings.warn("Requests is running with a non urllib3 backend, cannot retrieve server certificate for CBT", NoCertificateRetrievedWarning)
else:
    hash_object = hashlib.sha256(server_certificate)
    certificate_hash = hash_object.hexdigest().upper()
```

I see. Indeed, 10K function calls is a lot, and this harks to a downside of using binding :( It's hard to determine what logic runs when notifications trigger. Lets just use `this` then. Could you add a comment to `tf-op-table-entry` noting why we pass in the table?

Another thing you could do is make `tf-op-table` pass a callback to `tf-op-table-entry` that is called within `_handleHeaderClick ` after expansion is toggled, ie

in `tf-op-table-entry`:

```js
// A callback called when the header is clicked.
// The callback is passed this table entry.
headerClickCallback: Object,
...
_handleHeaderClick: function(e) {
  this.expanded ^= true;
  if (this.headerClickCallback) {
    this.headerClickCallback(this);
  }
  this.classList.add('selected');
},
```

and then in `tf-op-table`:

```html
<tf-op-table-entry ... headerClickCallback="[[_headerClickCallback]]"> ...
```

```js
_handleHeaderClick: {
  type: Object,
  readOnly: true,
  // This property returns a function that returns a function.
  // We actually want this property to be a function, and polymer calls
  // the higher-level function first to initialize the property.
  value: () => ((newlySelectedEntry) => {
    if (this._selectedEntry) {
      // TODO(chizeng): Define an isSelected property on the entry, and have the
      // entry toggle its own class. The table would merely set `isSelected` on the
      // entry.
      this._selectedEntry.classList.remove('selected');
    }
    this._selectedEntry = newlySelectedEntry;
    this.selected = newlySelectedEntry.node;
  }),
},
```

The advantage here is that each component is only deals with itself. `tf-op-table` should not have to set classes on `tf-op-table-entry`,  and `tf-op-table-entry` should not have to manipulate properties of `tf-op-table` directly.

That being said, it seems like you all gave good thought to the design in terms of performance, so this has my approval either way.

As far as I can tell, the Windows build is failing because the [Windows implementation](https://github.com/openthread/openthread/blob/master/examples/drivers/windows/otApi/otApi.cpp#L2100) is conflicting with the [OpenThread implementation](https://github.com/openthread/openthread/blob/master/src/core/openthread.cpp#L1615).

One fix could be to make the C++ call directly:
```
aInstance->mThreadNetif.GetActiveDataset().GetLocal().Get(dataset);
```

@nibanks, any thoughts?
